Static, single-page browser viewer for the steno stroke-decision tree produced by the compiler; fetches `../out/viz-data.json` (must be served over http://, not `file://`) and lets a user click through category → root → axis/child choices, rendering each reached node as a keyboard diagram plus its multi-line/one-liner translation text. There is no build step — this is the entire app (markup, CSS, and vanilla JS all inline in one `<script>`).

The expected JSON shape (not defined here, only consumed) is `{ categories: [{label, roots: [key,...]}], nodes: { [key]: {axis, children, terminal, description, multiLine, oneLiner, oneLinerRoot} } }`. An `axis` node has `{kind: "count"|..., options: [{key,label}]}` and resolves to exactly one option's node before its preview/children are used — `resolve(key)` does this and asserts an option is never itself an axis node. Anywhere the tree has a single child, navigation auto-advances into it without user input (`isSingleton`), even chaining through multiple singleton axis nodes in a row; this auto-chained portion is never written into the `path` array, only real multi-way choices are, so `path` state stays valid across re-renders that change upstream selections. `buildRows()` self-heals `path` if a stored key no longer appears among the current children (because an upstream axis choice changed the tree shape) — it truncates `path` in place at the first mismatch rather than erroring.

`parseStroke(sub)` and the `LEFT_ORDER`/`MID_ORDER`/`RIGHT_ORDER` key-bank tables are a hand-maintained JS mirror of `parse_stroke`/`LEFT_ORDER`/`MID_ORDER`/`RIGHT_ORDER` in `crates/steno/src/stroke/keys.rs` — if the Rust parsing/bank-membership rules change, this file must be updated in lockstep or the keyboard diagrams will highlight the wrong keys. It's deliberately lenient (no error handling) since all input strings are pre-validated canonical output from the compiler. `TOP_ROW`/`BOTTOM_ROW`/`VOWEL_ROW` encode the physical stagger of a real steno keyboard (note row-1 col-10 `T` is a *right*-bank key while row-1 col-2 `T` is *left*-bank — same letter, different bank depending on grid position); `isActive` and `kbKey` render against this fixed 11-column grid.

Global mutable state driving `render()`: `activeCategory`, `path`, `oneLinerActive` (one global multi-line/one-liner preference — lineflag.rs treats this as per-construct, never per-stroke), `axisSelection` (a `Map` remembering each axis node's chosen option across re-renders), and `currentOneLinerRoot` (recomputed each render from whichever row's node carries `oneLinerRoot`, used by `displayKey` to splice an augmented first-stroke segment into the displayed key when one-liner mode is on). `variantKeyFor(node)` picks which of `multiLine`/`oneLiner` text to show, preferring the active global toggle only when a node has both. There's no test harness or bundler; editing means editing this file directly and reloading against a locally-served `out/viz-data.json`.